# Ship clean — no guards, shims, or micro-files

## Fail fast — no unnecessary guards

Do not add defensive checks for invariants that callers already guarantee (required deps, constructor-injected services, module imports that must exist).

- If a value is required for the code path to make sense, use it directly. A missing value is a bug — let it throw so it gets fixed upstream.
- Do not add `if (!x) return`, optional chaining on required params, empty fallbacks, or silent no-ops to "be safe."
- Guards are OK only for real external boundaries: user input, network, file I/O, optional feature flags documented as optional.

```javascript
// ❌ BAD — masks upstream bug
function draw(pass) {
    if (!pass?.obstacleGrid) return;
    pass.obstacleGrid.grid[idx];
}

// ✅ GOOD — broken wiring fails immediately
function draw(pass) {
    pass.obstacleGrid.grid[idx];
}
```

## No micro-modules

Do not create new files for one to three tiny helpers that many files would import.

- Add helpers next to their primary consumer, or into an existing module that already owns that domain (`GridUtils.js`, `wallGridCells.js`, `Aabb2D.js`, etc.).
- Split into a new file only when the module is a coherent subsystem (many related exports, clear boundary) — not a single passthrough or 5-line wrapper.

## No passthrough / fallback / legacy in finished work

When implementing a change, remove the old path in the same pass. Do not leave:

- Re-exports or wrappers that only forward to the new API
- "Legacy" or "compat" branches "just in case"
- Duplicate functions where one calls the other with no added logic
- Commented-out old code or `TODO remove` cleanup deferred to a follow-up

If migration is genuinely multi-step, say so explicitly and list what still removes — do not ship interim redundancy as the default state.

## No in-memory migration theater

Sandbox/editor sim state is **runtime-only** unless explicitly persisted (save/load, localStorage, server). A page refresh starts clean.

- Do **not** add teardown/sync/migrate hooks so old in-memory representations "upgrade themselves" when the user didn't refresh.
- Do **not** keep dual paths (old Segment walls + new edge planes, `cellEdgeWalls` cleanup, "call sync after rotate to rebuild", etc.) "in case they didn't refresh."
- When replacing an approach, **delete the old path in the same pass** and wire the new one. Refresh is the migration.
- Do **not** tell the user to respawn, rotate, or manually rebuild props to pick up a dev iteration unless the feature **requires** that action for real gameplay reasons — not to clear your leftover state.

Migration code is OK only for **real persistence boundaries**: loaded saves, debounced storage, API payloads, schema version fields — places where refresh does **not** reset state.

```javascript
// ❌ BAD — legacy segment teardown on every spawn/rotate "just in case"
export function syncGridCellEdgeBarriers(state, prop) {
    teardownLegacySegments(state, prop);
}

// ✅ GOOD — one implementation; fresh session loads it
export function resolveEntityCellEdgeBarriers(state, entity) { /* ... */ }
```

## Extend shared libraries — do not reinvent

When implementing new behavior, **use and extend** the existing domain modules instead of duplicating logic inline or in a one-off helper file.

If a helper belongs in one of these modules (reused or clearly owned by that domain), add it there. If it is truly single-use and tiny, colocate with the primary caller — not a new micro-file.

```javascript
// ❌ BAD — local cardinal snap duplicate
function beltFacing(angle) {
    return Math.round(angle / (Math.PI / 2)) * (Math.PI / 2);
}

// ✅ GOOD — shared Angle API
import { quantizeCardinalAngle } from "../Math/Angle.js";
prop.facing = quantizeCardinalAngle(angle);
```

## Review bar before finishing

- Would removing a guard hide a real bug? If yes, fix the caller instead.
- Would this new file be imported from 5+ places for <20 lines total? Inline or extend an existing module.
- Is anything left that exists only because the old API used to? Delete it now.
- Did I add sync/teardown "for users who didn't refresh"? Remove it — refresh is not a migration scenario here.
